\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.5]{PCM.eps}\caption{}\label{fig6}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

Let us discuss now causal properties of the Minkowski space--time on the obtained diagram. Consider the fig. (\ref{fig7}). Here we show a time--like world--line of an observer or of a massive particle. It is the bold curly vertically directed line with the arrow. Also we depict on the fig. (\ref{fig7}) a space--like Cauchy surface --- a surface of a fixed time slice, $t=const$. It is the bold curly horizontally directed line. From the picture under consideration it is not hard to see that any observer in this space--time can access (view) whole space--like sections as he reaches future infinity, $I^+$. Hence, in Minkowski space--time there are no regions which are causally disconnected from each other. Below we will see that the situation in the case of Schwarzschild space--time is quite different.

