{\bf 1.} In this lecture we find a solution of Einstein equations which describes a stable star --- an ideal ball of matter surrounded by vacuum. This is referred to as \underline{interior solution}. Inside the ball we assume that the energy--momentum tensor is not zero, $T_{\mu\nu} \neq 0$, but it is homogeneous and spherically symmetric. At the same time outside the ball there is vacuum, i.e. $T_{\mu\nu} = 0$ and $\Lambda = 0$.

To have a stable star, inside it there should be a matter, which is capable to create a strong enough pressure to prevent its collapse. Hence, $T_{\mu\nu}$ of a dust, which was considered in the previous lectures, is not sufficient. The appropriate energy momentum tensor is given by

\begin{eqnarray}\label{EMTpf}
T_{\mu\nu}(\underline{x}) = \rho(\underline{x}) \, u_\mu(\underline{x}) \, u_\nu(\underline{x}) + p(\underline{x}) \, \left[u_\mu(\underline{x})^{\phantom{\frac12}} u_\nu(\underline{x}) - g_{\mu\nu}(\underline{x})\right],
\end{eqnarray}
where $g_{\mu\nu}$ is the metric tensor and $\underline{x} = \left(t, \vec{x}\right)$ is the coordinate four--vector. We start with providing arguments that this is the \underline{energy momentum tensor} \underline{for a relativistic perfect fluid} and $\rho$ is the energy density, while $p$ is the pressure. In fact, in the reference system, where the fluid is static its four--velocity is $u^\mu = \left(g_{00}^{-\frac12},0,0,0\right)$ and then

\begin{eqnarray}
\left|\left|T^\mu_\nu\right|\right| = Diag\left(\rho, - p, - p, - p\right), \quad T^\mu_\nu = g^{\mu\alpha} \, T_{\alpha\nu}.
\end{eqnarray}
Already this form of the tensor can reveal the physical meaning of $\rho$ and $p$, as follows from the course of classical electrodynamics.

Furthermore, the condition of the conservation of this energy momentum tensor is as follows:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{cons1}
0 = D^\mu\, T_{\mu\nu} = \left(\rho + p\right) \, u_\mu \, D^\mu u_\nu + D^\mu\left[(\rho + p)\, u_\mu\right]\, u_\nu - D_\nu p.
\end{eqnarray}
Multiplying this equality by $u^\nu$ and using that $u^\nu \, u_\nu = 1$ (and, hence, $u^\nu \, D^\mu u_\nu = 0$), we arrive at the following equation:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{cont1}
D^\mu\left[\left(\rho + p\right)\, u_\mu\right] - u^\mu \, D_\mu p = D^\mu\left[\rho \, u_\mu\right] + p\, D^\mu\, u_\mu = 0.
\end{eqnarray}
The last equality is just a covariant generalization of the continuity equation in the flat space--time: $\partial^\mu \left[\rho \, u_\mu\right] = \dot{\rho} + div \left[\rho \vec{v}\right] = 0.$ Note that in the non--relativistic limit the pressure is always much less than the energy density, $p \ll \rho$, for the same reason as why non--relativistic kinetic energy is much smaller than the rest energy.

Using (\ref{cons1}) and (\ref{cont1}), we find the following equation:

\begin{eqnarray}
\left(\rho + p\right)\, u_\mu \, D^\mu u_\nu = \left(\delta^\alpha_\nu - u^\alpha \, u_\nu\right)\, D_\alpha p,
\end{eqnarray}
Here $\left|\left|\delta^\alpha_\nu - u^\alpha \, u_\nu\right|\right| = Diag(0,1,1,1)$ --- is the projector on spatial directions. Hence, this is a relativistic, covariant extension of the Euler equation for a liquid without viscosity:

\begin{eqnarray}
\rho \left[\partial_t \vec{v} + \left(\vec{v}, \vec{\nabla}\right)\, \vec{v}\right] = - \vec{\nabla}p.
\end{eqnarray}
The last equation is just the Newton's second law, $m \, \vec{a} = \vec{F}$, both sides of which are attributed per unit volume. In fact,

