\includegraphics[scale=0.5]{wave.eps}\caption{}\label{fig17}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

{\bf 4.} To complete our study of the gravitational energy--momentum pseudo--tensor let us calculate the energy--momentum carried by the above free gravitational wave. As we have seen above, for
the gravitational wave $h^\mu_\mu = 0$. Hence, $|g| \approx |\eta| = 1$. Furthermore, at the linear order

\begin{eqnarray}
G^{\mu\nu}_{,\alpha} \approx g^{\mu\nu}_{,\alpha} \approx - h^{\mu\nu}_{,\alpha}.
\end{eqnarray}
As the result, for the \underline{free plane--wave} the non--zero contributions to $t_{\mu\nu}$ in (\ref{tmunu}) are contained in the term as follows:

\begin{eqnarray}
\frac12 \, g^{\mu\alpha} \, g^{\nu\beta} \, g_{\gamma\delta} \, g_{\sigma\xi} \, g^{\gamma\xi}_{,\alpha} \, g^{\delta\sigma}_{,\beta} \approx \frac12 \, h^{\alpha,\mu}_\beta \, h^{\beta,\nu}_\alpha.
\end{eqnarray}
Thus, in this case we obtain that

\begin{eqnarray}
t^{\mu\nu} \approx \frac{1}{32\, \pi \, \kappa} \, h^{\alpha,\mu}_\beta \, h^{\beta,\nu}_\alpha.
\end{eqnarray}
For the plane--wave under consideration we have that $h_{\mu\nu}(\underline{x}) = h_{\mu\nu}(t-z)$ and the only non--zero components are $h_{11} = - h_{22}$ and $h_{12} = h_{21}$. Then the only non--vanishing component of $t_{\mu\nu}$ is equal to:

\begin{eqnarray}
t^{03} \approx \frac{1}{16 \, \pi \, \kappa} \, \left[\dot{h}_{12}^2 + \dot{h}_{11}^2\right].
\end{eqnarray}
This means that we have energy flux in the third direction --- in the direction of the wave propagation.


