\centerline{\bf \Large LECTURE XII}

{\it  Geometry of the de Sitter space--time. Geometry of the anti--de Sitter space--time.}

\vspace{10mm}

{\bf 1.} So far we always have been setting the cosmological constant, $\Lambda$, to zero. In this lecture we find the most symmetric and simplest (so to say ground state) solutions of the Einstein equations in the case when $\Lambda \neq 0$, but $T_{\mu\nu} = 0$. Note, however, that the standard energy--momentum tensor,

\begin{eqnarray}
T_{\mu\nu} = \rho \, u_\mu \, u_\nu + p\, \left(u_\mu\, u_\nu - g_{\mu\nu}\right),
\end{eqnarray}
with $p = - \rho$, i.e. $w = -1$, describes the same situation, $T_{\mu\nu} = \rho \, g_{\mu\nu}$, as non--zero cosmological constant, if $\rho = const$. Hence, one can find the metrics that are defined below using the methods of the previous lecture, but for many reasons we prefer the pure geometric picture/language adopted here.

$D$-dimensional space--time of constant curvature solves the following equation:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{first}
G_{\alpha\beta} = \pm \frac{(D-1)(D-2)}{2}\, H^2 \, g_{\alpha\beta}, \quad \alpha, \beta = 0, \dots, D-1.
\end{eqnarray}
Here $G_{\alpha\beta}$ is the Einstein tensor and $H$ is the Hubble constant:

\begin{eqnarray}
\Lambda = \frac{(D-1)\, (D-2)}{2} \, H^2.
\end{eqnarray}
In this equation ``$+$'' sign corresponds to the space--time of constant positive curvature. At the same time ``$-$'' sign corresponds to the space--time of constant negative curvature. The reason for that is explained below.

{\bf 2.} $D$-dimensional \underline{de Sitter space--time}, that of the constant {\it positive} curvature, can be realized as the following hyperboloid,

\begin{eqnarray}\label{hyp}
- \left(X^0\right)^2 + \left(X^1\right)^2 + \dots + \left(X^D\right)^2 \equiv - \eta_{AB} \, X^A \, X^B = H^{-2}, \quad A,B = 0, \dots, D,
\end{eqnarray}
placed into the ambient $(D+1)$-dimensional Minkowski space--time, with the metric $ds^2 = \eta_{AB} \, dX^A \, dX^B$. One way to see that a metric on such a hyperboloid solves equation (\ref{first}) is to observe that it can be obtained from the sphere via the analytical continuation $X^{D+1} \to i\, X^0$. This is referred to as \underline{Wick rotation}. In fact, after such a change of coordinates the ambient Minkowski space--time is transformed into the Euclidian one. At the same time, the equation (\ref{hyp}) is transformed into the one defining $D$--dimensional sphere. Note that the Wick rotation does not change the sign of the curvature.

For illustrative reasons we depict two-dimensional de Sitter space--time on the fig. \ref{fig20}. Here each constant $X_0$ slice of this two-dimensional de Sitter space--time is the circle of the radius $(H^{-2} + X_0^2)$.

Another way to see that the hyperboloid in question has a constant curvature is to observe that eq. (\ref{hyp}) is invariant under $SO(D,1)$ Lorentz transformations of the ambient space--time. The stabilizer of arbitrary point, say $\left(X^0, X^1, X^2, \dots X^D\right) = \left(0,1/H,0, \dots, 0\right)$, obeying (\ref{hyp}) is $SO(D-1,1)$ group. Hence, the de Sitter space--time is \underline{homogeneous}, $SO(D,1)/SO(D-1,1)$, manifold and any its point is equivalent to another one. Furthermore, all directions at every point are equivalent to each other up to the difference between space and time. (Compare this with the sphere, which is $SO(D+1)/SO(D)$.) Thus, $SO(D,1)$ Lorentz group of the ambient Minkowski space is the \underline{de Sitter isometry group}.

The geodesic distance, $L_{12}$, between two points, $X_1^A$ and $X_2^A$, on the hyperboloid can be conveniently expressed via the so-called \underline{hyperbolic distance}, $Z_{12}$, as follows:

\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{\cos \left(H \,L_{12}\right)}{H^2} \equiv \frac{Z_{12}}{H^2} \equiv - \eta_{AB}\, X^A_1 \, X^B_2, \quad {\rm where} \quad - \eta_{AB} \, X^A_{1,2} \, X^B_{1,2} = H^{-2}.
\end{eqnarray}
To better understand the meaning of this expression, it is instructive to compare it to the geodesic distance, $l_{12}$, on a sphere of radius $R$:

prevtext:
where $B$ is the body of the star, $d^3V\sqrt{g^{(3)}}$ is the volume form of the three--dimensional time--slice, following from the metric (\ref{starsol}). Correspondingly $g^{(3)}$ is the determinant of the three--dimensional spatial part of the metric (\ref{starsol}). Thus, the difference $E_{bin} = M_{real} - M > 0$ is the gravitational binding energy.

Coming back to (\ref{Eeqr}), from the second equation we find that

\begin{eqnarray}\label{Newtpoten}
\frac{d\nu}{dr} = \frac{2\, \kappa \, M(r) + 8\,\pi \, r^3 \, \kappa \, p}{r \, \left[r - 2\, \kappa\, M(r)\right]}.
\end{eqnarray}
In the Newtonian limit, $p\ll \rho$ and $\kappa \, M(r) \ll r$, this equation reduces to
$d\nu/dr \approx 2\, \kappa\, M(r)/r^2$, i.e. to the spherically symmetric version of the Poisson equation for the gravitational potential. Thus, in the case of the static, spherically symmetric gravitational field, $\nu/2$ has the meaning of the relativistic analog of the Newtonian potential.

Instead of the last equation in (\ref{Eeqr}) it is convenient to use the condition of the conservation of the energy--momentum tensor, $D^\mu \, T_{\mu\nu} = 0$. In our case it reduces to the following equation:

\begin{eqnarray}
2\, \frac{dp}{dr} = - \left(p + \rho\right)\, \frac{d\nu}{dr}.
\end{eqnarray}
Hence, using eq. (\ref{Newtpoten}) here, we obtain:

\begin{eqnarray}\label{ToOpVo}
\frac{dp}{dr} = - \left(p + \rho\right)\, \frac{\kappa \, M(r) + 4\,\pi \, r^3 \, \kappa \, p}{r \, \left[r - 2\, \kappa\, M(r)\right]},
\end{eqnarray}
which is the so called \underline{Tolman--Oppenheimer--Volkoff equation} for the hydrodynamic equilibrium of the star. In the Newtonian limit, $p \ll \rho$ and $\kappa\, M(r) \ll r$, this equation reduces to:

\begin{eqnarray}
\frac{dp}{dr} \approx - \rho \, \frac{\kappa \, M(r)}{r^2}.
\end{eqnarray}

{\bf 3.} In conclusion, we have found that the metric for a homogeneous, static, spherically symmetric and non--rotating star is as follows:

\begin{eqnarray}
ds^2 = e^{\nu(r)} \, dt^2 - \frac{dr^2}{1 - \frac{2\, \kappa\, M(r)}{r}} - r^2\, d\Omega^2,
\end{eqnarray}
where $M(r)$ is defined in (\ref{M(r)}), while $\nu(r)$ follows from (\ref{Newtpoten}). At the same time, the necessary and sufficient condition of the star equilibrium is given by the equation (\ref{ToOpVo}).

Outside the star body $p=0$ and $\rho=0$, hence, one can solve (\ref{Newtpoten}) to find that $e^\nu = 1 - \frac{2\,\kappa\, M(R)}{r}$. As the result outside the star surface, $r\geq R$, the solution under consideration reduces to the Schwarzschild one.

To solve the equations (\ref{M(r)}), (\ref{Newtpoten}) and (\ref{ToOpVo}) explicitly one has to specify the equation of state $p = p(\rho)$. The simplest model corresponds to the incompressible fluid, when $\rho = \rho_0 = const$. Then $M(r) = \frac{4\, \pi}{3}\, r^3 \, \rho_0$ for $r<R$ and the solution of (\ref{ToOpVo}) is as follows:

\begin{eqnarray}
p(r) = \rho_0 \, \frac{\sqrt{1 - \frac{2\, \kappa\, M}{R}} - \sqrt{1 - \frac{2\, \kappa \, M \, r^2}{R^3}}}{\sqrt{1 - \frac{2\, \kappa\, M \, r^2}{R^3}} - 3 \, \sqrt{1 - \frac{2\, \kappa \, M}{R}}}, \quad M = \frac{4\pi}{3}\, R^3 \, \rho_0.
\end{eqnarray}
From this equation it is not hard to see that the central pressure $p(r=0)$ blows up to infinity if $R = \frac{9}{4}\, \kappa \, M$. That simply means that stars with $M > M_{max} = \frac{4}{9\kappa}\, R$ cannot exist, if their matter consists of the incompressible fluid.

